<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-007-159 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 612 538</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 25 1991 v25 n47 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC coaxes RBOCs to unbundle network services. (U.S. FederalCommunications Commission) (regional Bell operating companies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) wants the regionalBell holding companies (RBOCs) to unbundle their network services,and the agency has started an inquiry into the future of thepublic networks to reach this objective.andP;  The FCC's goal is toeventually allow providers and users of enhanced data and voiceservices greater access to pubic networks.andP;  It has already givenpermission to the RBOCs to provide enhanced services.andP;  Thecompanies can offer the services without having to channel theservices through their separate business units.andP;  The RBOCs areusing a concept, Open Network Architecture, to move embeddedsoftware utilized to process and route calls into centralized datacenters instead of local switches.andP;  In this way, the software canbe tailored to the individual needs of specific users.andP;  The FCC isconcerned that reliability and security be maintained and isseeking feedback on how to balance security needs with greaterpublic network accessibility.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data CommunicationsTelecommunications ServicesVoice CommunicationsBell Regional Holding CompaniesUnited States. Federal Communications Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>